<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Accelerated Aging" class="currentChild" href="Accelerated_Aging">Accelerated Aging</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A process used to estimate the <a title="Permanence" href="Permanence">permanence</a> of paper or other <a title="Substrate" href="Substrate">substrate</a>. Depending on a paper's chemical composition, it can have varying levels of longevity. Since normal aging is not practical, procedures have been developed to simulate the aging process in a much shorter period of time. Accelerated aging uses either the "dry method," in which a paper sample is aged in a 105ºC oven for a set period of time, and examined for reduced strength, brittleness, reduced <a title="Tearing Resistance" href="Tearing_Resistance">tearing resistance</a>, <a title="Folding Endurance" href="Folding_Endurance">folding endurance</a>, etc., or the "moist method," which ages the paper at 90ºC at 25% <a title="Relative Humidity" href="Relative_Humidity">relative humidity</a>. The fibers of <a title="Cellulose" href="Cellulose">cellulose</a> that make up a paper deteriorate more rapidly in the presence of moisture, so it is believed that the moist method more closely approximates the natural aging of a paper. (See also <a title="Permanence" href="Permanence">Permanence</a>.) 
</p>
